metadata.name: untitled
metadata.description:
digital painting, air brush, oil paint, photo collage

Working in the oscillating position between reality and the digital, Tyler Cala Williams seeks to pose questions toward numerous power dynamics in their life with surrealist paintings and photo abstraction. Using photography and found images as a foundation for all their work, Williams aims to reflect back to their audience the sadomasochistic relationships that govern life and its precarious placement. Their graffiti/tagging esc alteration to photos motion a nudge of acknowledgment to the already unstable hierarchies that are inescapable to all of us.  
Williams imagines a reality where masochism bears the capacity to subvert and potentially smudge the borders between the powerful and powerless. Harkening back to surrealism, Williams dissects the subconscious mind within their painterly-like photo collages, in an attempt to discover the proper tools that can bugger western power structures.
